To solve the system of linear equations using the matrix method, we first write the system in the matrix form AX = B, where A is the matrix of coefficients, X is the column vector of variables, and B is the column vector of constants.

A = \begin{bmatrix}
4 & -3 & 0.5 \\
2 & 5 & 1 \\
1 & -1 & 2
\end{bmatrix}

X = \begin{bmatrix}
x \\
y \\
z
\end{bmatrix}

B = \begin{bmatrix}
6.2 \\
9.9 \\
-0.1
\end{bmatrix}

Now, we can find the inverse of matrix A, denoted as A_inv, and then multiply it by B to get the solution X:

X = A_inv * B

First, we find the inverse of A:

A_inv = \begin{bmatrix}
0.246 & 0.066 & -0.082 \\
0.082 & 0.164 & -0.041 \\
-0.123 & 0.033 & 0.541
\end{bmatrix}

Now, we multiply A_inv by B:

X = \begin{bmatrix}
0.246 & 0.066 & -0.082 \\
0.082 & 0.164 & -0.041 \\
-0.123 & 0.033 & 0.541
\end{bmatrix} * \begin{bmatrix}
6.2 \\
9.9 \\
-0.1
\end{bmatrix}

X = \begin{bmatrix}
1.99 \\
2.01 \\
-1.00
\end{bmatrix}

So, the solution to the system of equations is approximately (x, y, z) = (1.99, 2.01, -1.00), rounded to two decimal places.
